SP  - 292
EP  - 300
DO  - 10.1109/ISRIMT67769.2025.11412991
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105035080756?origin=resultslist
AB  - The transition of automotive manufacturing towards small-batch, customized production highlights the limitations of traditional flexible assembly lines, which are prone to mixed-model and misassembly errors. While the island-based flexible workshop model mitigates these quality issues through modular workstation layouts, its distributed nature introduces significant logistical complexity in material delivery, making coordinated multi-AGV scheduling a critical bottleneck for lean production efficiency. This study addresses the engineering challenge of multi-AGV collaborative scheduling by constructing a comprehensive workshop model that integrates multi-dimensional constraints, including pedestrian dynamics, AGV load-dependent energy consumption, and equipment heterogeneity. A dual-loop decision model based on deep reinforcement learning (DRL) is developed to simultaneously resolve task allocation and path conflict problems. Experimental results in a typical scenario involving 5 assembly islands and 3 vehicle models demonstrate that the proposed method reduces the required AGV fleet size by 16.67% and achieves an average maximum completion time of 32.9 time units, outperforming traditional genetic algorithm approaches. Furthermore, the DRL algorithm exhibits superior computational efficiency and stable performance across varying problem scales, confirming its strong generalization capabilities and collaborative advantages for diverse industrial environments. © 2025 IEEE.
