C7  - 141282D
DO  - 10.1117/12.3101627
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033019186?origin=resultslist
AB  - This study addresses multi-depot cold-chain vehicle scheduling, a setting characterized by high-dimensional dynamics, tight time windows, and stringent temperature control. We develop a multiagent reinforcement learning (MARL) framework with centralized training and decentralized execution, where agents' state representations integrate geo-location, residual payload, chamber temperature deviation, remaining service time, and depot/task proximity. The global Critic aggregates shared environmental signals and updates are synchronized via parameter averaging, while experience replay and temporal-difference learning stabilize policy improvement under frequent reallocations. A reproducible simulation environment is built in Python/PyTorch with Ray RLlib, and experiments are instantiated using 2024 operational records from a provincial capital logistics provider comprising six depots, 132 customer nodes, and 458 tasks. Performance is evaluated on average delivery delay, energy consumption, task completion rate, and convergence iterations against genetic algorithm, enhanced ant colony optimization, and deep Q-network (DQN) -based single-agent baselines. Results indicate consistently superior scheduling quality and faster, more stable convergence of the proposed MARL, yielding balanced cross-depot task allocation and improved resource utilization under temperature constraints. The findings demonstrate that coupling global value estimation with decentralized execution is effective for scalable, constraint-aware optimization in intelligent cold-chain logistics. © COPYRIGHT SPIE. Downloading of the abstract is permitted for personal use only.
