AB  - AbstractThe increasing penetration of distributed energy resources and flexible loads in residential sectors requires advanced optimization methods to ensure cost-effective, reliable, and sustainable energy use. This paper presents a constraint-aware demand-side management (DSM) framework for smart homes that integrates photovoltaic (PV) generation, battery energy storage systems (BESS), and electric vehicles (EV) under real day-ahead pricing signals. A hybrid optimization approach based on the Zebra Optimization Algorithm (ZOA) is developed to co-schedule household appliances and distributed resources while maintaining user-defined comfort constraints. Three operating scenarios are compared: unscheduled consumption, optimal load scheduling without DSM, and full DSM integration. Performance is assessed through electricity cost, peak-to-average ratio (PAR), and load profile characteristics. The simulation results in this work indicate that the total cost of energy consumption was $30.5 in the first scenario, $27.9 in the second, and $26 in the third. The proposed method highlights the role of intelligent DSM strategies in enabling cost savings, peak shaving, and improved sustainability in residential energy systems. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.
