AB  - Unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) present a promising solution for collecting data from the Internet of Things devices (IoTDs) in communication-constrained scenarios. However, the heterogeneity and dynamism of IoTDs, coupled with environmental uncertainties, significantly impede the data collection process. This further leads to variable device data loads, time-sensitive scheduling, and unpredictable situations that must be addressed. Therefore, we aim to develop an efficient scheduling strategy for UAVs that balances global optimization with local adaptive adjustments. In this paper, we propose a novel hierarchical scheduling framework—REFINED. In the upper layer, inspired by multi-objective evolutionary algorithms, REFINED initially identifies the devices requiring service through non-dominated sorting. It then employs a multi-head attention-based reinforcement learning method to find optimal scheduling strategies. Notably, the pre-trained model maintains strong adaptability under scale variations and outperforms traditional algorithms in solution efficiency. In the lower layer, we propose an enhanced deep deterministic policy gradient algorithm to tackle dynamic demand-induced collection efficiency problems. By discarding the centralized full-information assumption, we train a lightweight model deployed distributively on UAVs, enabling online adjustment of resource allocation. Extensive simulation experiments demonstrate that REFINED is highly effective in dynamic data collection, offering superior scalability and increased efficiency. © 2025 Elsevier B.V. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.
