AB  - This paper proposes a GAN-enhanced Soft Actor-Critic (GAN-SAC) framework for urban multi-agent vehicle scheduling. Traditional reinforcement learning methods face low training efficiency in sparse reward and high-dimensional action spaces. GAN-SAC uses a Generative Adversarial Network to generate synthetic reward signals, aiding policy learning, improving value evaluation and updates. It combines an embedding layer with an attention mechanism to handle vehicle and request features, and integrates a double Q-network and entropy regularization for multi-agent interactions. Experiments on real urban data show that GAN-SAC outperforms traditional SAC and other baselines, improving scheduling efficiency, reducing waiting time, and increasing order acceptance rate. In sparse reward environments, it converges faster and has a more stable learning process, offering a practical solution for urban intelligent transportation. © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
