TI  - A federated transformer-based framework for uncertainty-aware and privacy-preserving EV scheduling with digital twin reinforcement learning
PY  - 2026
T2  - Electric Power Systems Research
VL  - 258
C7  - 113021
DO  - 10.1016/j.epsr.2026.113021
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105034583006?origin=resultslist
AB  - The accelerating adoption of electric vehicles (EVs) presents new challenges for intelligent, adaptive, and privacy-preserving charge/discharge scheduling. This paper introduces a unified framework that integrates a federated multi-task Transformer with digital twin-enhanced reinforcement learning to perform real-time, uncertainty-aware EV scheduling. The Transformer jointly forecasts key behavioral parameters–arrival time, departure time, and travel mileage–by capturing temporal-spatial dependencies across distributed EV fleets while preserving user privacy through federated learning. A high-fidelity digital twin simulates user behavior, grid conditions, and EV battery dynamics, enabling continual policy adaptation through reinforcement learning. Additionally, conformal prediction is employed to quantify uncertainty and guide decision-making, improving robustness under dynamic and non-stationary environments. Extensive simulations on real-world mobility data demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed framework. Forecasting accuracy exceeds R2 > 0.99 for arrival time and 0.98 for travel mileage across clusters. In aggregator net revenue optimization, the proposed method delivers up to 15.09% improvement with V2G discharging and over 14% without V2G, outperforming state-of-the-art GAN and TCN baselines. By jointly addressing forecasting, uncertainty quantification, policy learning, and privacy preservation, the proposed framework offers a practical and scalable solution for next-generation EV-grid integration. © 2026 Elsevier B.V.
