UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105025799512?origin=resultslist
AB  - Quay cranes (QCs) and port vehicles, such as straddle carriers and yard trucks (YTs), are essential equipment for container handling at automated container terminals, and their scheduling issues strongly impact port efficiency and productivity. Optimization problems typically include QC assignment problems, QC scheduling problems, and vehicle routing problems. This study aimed to define an optimal sequence for the QCs to handle the containers from a vessel and then determine the shortest routing plan for the YTs to move those containers to the depots. A deep-learning-enhanced quantum optimization algorithm was proposed to optimize QC scheduling, whereas the shortest routes for YTs were determined using deep reinforcement learning. A hybrid metaheuristic filter was employed to explore quantum-approximated optimization. We implemented a deep learning algorithm to accelerate the development of quantum computing algorithms for solving complex optimization problems. The performance and robustness of the proposed method were demonstrated via numerical simulations of real-world scenarios. The results were validated using a real dataset from South Korea's Busan New Port (KRBNP), including specifications for real equipment (ship size, bay size, gantry speed, hoisting speed, etc.) and the layout configuration for 20-foot and 40-foot shipping containers. The number of tasks in the simulation is chosen as a scaled version of the actual handling of COSCO vessels (43 bays in total). The final results were statistically significant compared with a real dataset from UNCTAD and the World Bank Group, yielding improvements of 5.267 % and 2.588 % in QC productivity and utilization, respectively. This highlighted the practicality of different algorithms in managerial scenarios and underscored the approach to implementing highly promising variational quantum algorithms to solve optimal scheduling and routing problems for port equipment. © 2025 Elsevier B.V.
