DO  - 10.1016/j.eswa.2025.130007
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105023833302?origin=resultslist
AB  - This paper investigates the unmanned aerial vehicle scheduling problem (UAVSP) under gridded battlefield and logistics management. Compared with traditional scheduling problems that focus on task allocation and path planning, the battlefield UAVSP requires additional consideration of the military-specific factors of cargo conflict constraints (such as munitions versus flammable items, and food versus chemicals), i.e., different classes of materials cannot be transported by the same UAV at the same time. Therefore, in this paper, a mixed-integer linear programming (MILP) model is developed with the objective of minimizing the transportation cost, including transportation time and the number of UAVs used. Then, a two-stage self-learning Jaya algorithm (TSJA) is introduced, where the first stage dynamically records operation success rates to build a knowledge base, while the second stage leverages this knowledge to intelligently guide operation selection. Finally, three transportation strategy self-organization methods are proposed to reduce the transportation cost. In terms of solution quality, experimental results show that the TSJA outperforms the other algorithms. © 2025 Published by Elsevier Ltd.
