AB  - Intelligent warehousing logistics systems employ Automated Guided Vehicles (AGVs) to fulfill the requirements of intelligent logistics transportation services. Single AGV control technology is mature, capable of handling large-scale complex path applications including intersecting paths. However, there are technical challenges in the cooperative control of multiple AGVs within dynamic and complex computational spaces. These challenges necessitate the utilization of various computational methods for path planning, to meet obstacle avoidance requirements, prevent spatial deadlock, and prevent obstructions from blocking the progress of AGVs. Centered on AGV motion control and taking path planning as the foundation, this paper primarily examines the concentrated conflicts that arise in the dynamic operation zones of multiple AGVs. Given the complexity of the traffic conditions in the algorithms employed, the DQN algorithm and neural network fitting have been incorporated to enhance the Q-value, thereby reinforcing the path planning and scheduling efficiency in intricate scenarios. For the prevalent conflicts in multi-AGV dynamic scheduling, a cooperative control approach for avoidance is proposed. This takes into account the AGV's current coordinates, as well as the restrictions at intersections, to determine whether to wait or avoid. Rules are established so that different path conflicts can pass in an orderly fashion at intersections, avoiding congestion and collisions.  © 2023 IEEE.
