AB  - The Bus Scheduling Problem (BSP) is a critical challenge in public transit systems. While many metaheuristic approaches offer high computational efficiency for large-scale problem instances, they often sacrifice solution quality, particularly in terms of bus utilization, by favoring speed over solution quality. In this paper, we propose a Memetic-Branch-and-Price (MBP) algorithm to address BSP in real-world scenarios, aiming to enhance bus utilization while maintaining computational tractability. First, a Memetic Algorithm (MA) is used to generate a high-quality initial scheduling solution that covers all trips, leveraging its ability to explore large solution spaces and avoid premature convergence. Next, we introduce a Conflict-Minimizing Selection Strategy to identify a subset of trips within this solution that holds high potential for further optimization. Finally, an exact Branch-and-Price (B&P) method is applied to refine this subset, significantly improving the overall schedule quality. MBP is evaluated on real-world data from the Qingdao bus company. Experimental results indicate that MBP produces schedules with improved bus utilization and cost efficiency, while outperforming standalone MA and B&P methods in both solution quality and runtime. © 2025 Elsevier B.V.
