AB  - Electric vehicles (EVs) have the potential to charge during low-price periods (G2V) and discharge to households during high-price periods (V2H), making them flexible demand response (DR) resources for home energy systems (HES). However, HES DR optimization faces significant uncertainty due to variations in user behavior and environmental conditions. To address this, this study proposes an HES DR Optimization Scheme Integrating DRL, Considering User Travel Demands and EV C/D Applications. First, an HES management framework is established. Then, an EV dynamic energy-switching model based on predicted travel plans and appliance models are constructed. Finally, a twin delayed deep deterministic policy gradient (TD3) algorithm for HES DR optimization is designed to achieve adaptive control under uncertainty. Simulation results show that, on an i7-12700 processor, the proposed method reduces energy costs by 36.52% compared with non-DR schemes and converges within 553.4 s, requiring only one-third of the convergence episodes of PPO. © 2025 IEEE.
